<Window xmlns="https://github.com/avaloniaui"
        xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
        xmlns:vm="using:SquareClickerPointer.ViewModels"
        xmlns:views="using:SquareClickerPointer.Views"
        xmlns:d="http://schemas.microsoft.com/expression/blend/2008"
        xmlns:mc="http://schemas.openxmlformats.org/markup-compatibility/2006"
        mc:Ignorable="d" d:DesignWidth="260" d:DesignHeight="760"
        x:Class="SquareClickerPointer.Views.MainWindow"
        x:DataType="vm:MainWindowViewModel"
        Icon="/Assets/avalonia-logo.ico"
        Title="SquareClickerPointer"
        SizeToContent="WidthAndHeight"
        Background="#1C1C1C">

    <Design.DataContext>
        <vm:MainWindowViewModel/>
    </Design.DataContext>

    <!--
    ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
     MainWindow layout
    ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

     WHY MainWindowViewModel does NOT mediate between the two controls:
     ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
     A common (but wrong) pattern is to put the "wiring" in the parent ViewModel:

         // MainWindowViewModel — BAD example
         public void OnDotMoved(double x, double y)
         {
             TriangleData.LastX = x;    // tightly coupled — knows both children
             TriangleData.Calculate();
         }

     This makes MainWindowViewModel a "god object" that knows about every child.
     Adding a third panel means editing MainWindowViewModel.  Deleting one panel
     means editing it again.  The parent becomes a bottleneck.

     Instead, the two controls communicate exclusively through DotPositionEventBus:

         PointControlViewModel  ──(DotReleased event)──►  DotPositionEventBus
                                                                    │
                                                                    ▼
                                                    TriangleAlphaDataViewModel

     MainWindow is just a container — it places the Views on screen and stays out
     of the communication.  Adding a fourth panel that reacts to the same event is
     zero changes to existing code; you just register a new subscriber.

     EACH CONTROL OWNS ITS OWN VIEWMODEL:
     ──────────────────────────────────────
     Both user controls set their own DataContext from Ioc.Default in their
     constructors.  MainWindow does not set or pass DataContext to them.
     This makes each control independently reusable — you could place
     PointControlView in a completely different window with the same result.
    -->

    <StackPanel Spacing="10" Margin="10">

        <!-- SquareClickerPointer — publisher of DotPositionEventBus.DotReleased -->
        <views:PointControlView/>

        <!-- TriangleAlphaData — subscriber to DotPositionEventBus.DotReleased -->
        <views:TriangleAlphaDataView/>

        <!--
        ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
         EXPANDABLE CONTAINERS
        ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

         Three independent ExpandableContainerView instances placed side-by-side
         (in a parent StackPanel here, but they work anywhere in a layout).

         EACH CONTAINER IS SELF-CONTAINED:
           • x:Name gives us a handle in MainWindow.axaml.cs so we can call
             Container1View.ViewModel.SetItems(…) to populate it externally.
           • Each container resolves its own Transient ExpandableContainerViewModel
             from the DI container inside its code-behind constructor.
           • They share the ContainerEventBus singleton — that is how accordion
             expand/collapse is coordinated without any direct references between them.

         NO MEDIATOR:
           MainWindow does not wire the containers together.  It only places them
           on screen and seeds their data.  The accordion behavior is handled
           entirely via the ContainerExpanded event on the shared ContainerEventBus.
           Adding a fourth container is one line of XAML and one seeding call —
           zero changes to the existing containers.
        -->
        <views:ExpandableContainerView x:Name="Container1View"/>
        <views:ExpandableContainerView x:Name="Container2View"/>
        <views:ExpandableContainerView x:Name="Container3View"/>

    </StackPanel>

</Window>
